&lt;b&gt;&quot;The temple has no place here&quot; - a banner against the &quot;SVO temple&quot; appeared in Russia&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Residents of Pushkin, St. Petersburg, continue to protest against the construction of the so-called &quot;SVO temple&quot; in a residential area. In the early hours of June 23, a banner with the inscription &quot;The temple has no place here&quot; appeared on the facade of one of the neighboring houses. In the morning, they began to remove it, eyewitnesses told the Bumaga publication.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The temple is planned to be built right in the courtyard of the high-rise buildings - the building will be as high as a ten-story house. The project is supported by the authorities: the governor Alexander Beglov and the Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation Sergey Lavrov participated in the ceremony of consecrating the pit.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Local residents insist: there is no place for construction among residential buildings. They propose to turn this place into a square. They express their protest with banners, graffiti and appeals to the authorities.&lt;/p&gt;

#russia #roc

Source channel: &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.me/shaltnotkill&quot;&gt;Christians against the war!&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;As a result of shelling, a UOC cathedral in Kyiv region was damaged&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On the night of June 23, the Russian army struck the city of Bila Tserkva in the Kyiv region. The attack damaged residential buildings, a hospital, and a number of civilian infrastructure facilities. One person was killed, eight were injured, including two rescuers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Spaso-Transfiguration Cathedral of the Orthodox Church of Ukraine (UOC) was also damaged. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/yevstr/posts/10080394608675399&quot;&gt;Archbishop Yevstraty (Zoria)&lt;/a&gt; reported the damage, citing photos published by priest &lt;b&gt;Mykola Hopaynich&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is one of the largest churches in the region. The blast wave from the explosions shattered the windows and caused visible damage to the building.&lt;/p&gt;

#ukraine #uoc

[Channel: &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.me/shaltnotkill&quot;&gt;Christians Against War!&lt;/a&gt;]

&lt;b&gt;As a result of shelling, a church and a gymnasium were damaged in the Nikopol region&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On the night of June 22, Russian troops carried out massive shelling of the Nikopol district of the Dnipropetrovsk region. According to &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.me/dnipropetrovskaODA/22371&quot;&gt;the head of the administration, Sergey Lysak&lt;/a&gt;, the strikes were carried out by FPV drones and heavy artillery.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Residential homes, a car, a gymnasium, and a religious institution - a church (not specified) - came under fire. Destruction was recorded in Nikopol itself, as well as in the Marganets and Mirovo communities.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fortunately, there were no casualties among the civilian population - people took shelter in time. Emergency services continue to eliminate the consequences of the attack.&lt;/p&gt;

#ukraine #destruction

Source channel: &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.me/shaltnotkill&quot;&gt;Christians Against War!&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;A director of an Orthodox center who supported the war was killed in Rostov.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In Rostov, Stanislav Goryainov, the head of the Orthodox anti-drug center &quot;Rostov without Drugs&quot;, died.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Someone called him at 10 pm on June 21. An hour later, he came covered in blood - his face, his hands. He undressed himself, and lay down. His tongue was very badly damaged, swollen. He couldn&#x27;t speak at all, just moaned. He showed his fist and [pointed] to his mouth. The ambulance came several times the next day. The doctor asked: &#x27;What happened? Were you beaten up? Who beat you up?&#x27; He showed his fist and [pointed] to his mouth. But [when asked about hospitalization] he waved his hands - &#x27;no, I won&#x27;t go&#x27;,&quot; his mother reported.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Rostov journalist Elena Romanova, who emigrated from Russia after the start of the full-scale war, noted on Facebook that the deceased &quot;quickly mounted the patriotic agenda and was at the disposal of the Rostov war arsonists&quot;. He accused those who left of betrayal and collected aid for the Russian military.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The journalist believes that he carried out his activities &quot;under the supervision and even at the behest of various comrade majors. He danced with the wolves and, apparently, stepped on someone&#x27;s tail.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

