&lt;b&gt;The World Council of Churches: &quot;These attacks exacerbate the crimes committed by the Russian authorities in the course of the ongoing invasion and war against the Ukrainian people&quot;&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From June 18 to 24, the governing body of the World Council of Churches - the Central Committee - met in Johannesburg, South Africa. The meeting addressed a number of thematic and personnel issues, as well as adopted a number of statements on important problems of the modern world, including the war in Ukraine.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the document &quot;Statement on Threats to Peace and Security of Peoples: A Kairos Moment for Just Peace&quot;, the World Council of Churches noted the horrific consequences of Russian aggression against Ukraine, the need for a peaceful resolution of the ongoing conflict, as well as Russia&#x27;s unwillingness to start peace negotiations and dialogue:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In Ukraine, intense missile strikes by Russia continue against civilian objects and infrastructure - for example, the attacks carried out in Kryvyi Rih on April 4 (20 civilians, including 9 children, were killed), in Sumy on Palm Sunday, April 13, 2025 (35 civilians, including children, were killed, more than 100 were injured), in Kyiv on June 17 (28 people were killed, at least 134 were injured), as well as in many other places almost daily. These attacks exacerbate the crimes committed by the Russian authorities in the course of the ongoing invasion and war against the Ukrainian people.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We also express concern about reports of strikes on passenger trains in the Bryansk and Kursk regions of Russia in late May and early June 2025, which are blamed on Ukraine.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Dialogue between Russia and Ukraine is currently being promoted by other states. The World Council of Churches in all cases of conflict or risk of its occurrence calls for dialogue and negotiations, not violence and the use of armed force, as only this path can lead to a sustainable peace. However, a dialogue imposed from the outside and not based on justice is not a genuine dialogue and cannot lead to a just and lasting peace. Moreover, despite calls for dialogue, Russia continues to escalate its attacks and campaign of terror against the Ukrainian people.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Central Committee:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;• Expresses deep concern about the suffering of the civilian population of Ukraine and Russia in the context of Russia&#x27;s invasion of Ukraine and condemns the escalation of attacks and the campaign of terror against the Ukrainian people.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;• Prays for peace in Ukraine and Russia - but for a just peace that does not reward the aggressor for his crimes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;• Calls for respect for freedom of religion and belief throughout the region.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;• Encourages the WCC General Secretary to continue to seek ways, with and through the churches of Russia and Ukraine, to improve the situation for the people of Ukraine and the entire region.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;• Requests the General Secretary to initiate theological dialogues on the war in Ukraine.&lt;/p&gt;

