&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&quot;You are not alone&quot;: how a Russian priest &quot;comforts&quot; wounded participants of the &quot;SVO&quot;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The archpriest from Vyazma, Valery Kalinin, travels to hospitals where wounded Russian soldiers are lying, and &lt;a href=&quot;https://xn--80ajkaheecehihanngfw8vja.xn--p1ai/news/intervyu/protoierey-valeriy-kalinin-samoe-glavnoe-v-gospitale-obyasnyat-boytsam-chto-oni-ne-odni/&quot;&gt;conducts&lt;/a&gt; conversations, services, confessions and communions with them. According to him, the main task is to convince the soldiers that they are &quot;not alone&quot; and &quot;needed by their loved ones, the country and God&quot;. Many of them, he claims, feel abandoned and forgotten.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In an interview, Kalinin acknowledges that &quot;just talking, stroking the head and hugging&quot; is sometimes more important than any words. He also talks about attempts to establish contact with the families of the military, but laments that many mothers and wives have a poor understanding of church life. Despite this, he continues his &quot;ministry&quot; - comforts, convinces, reminds of the &quot;immortal soul&quot; and the &quot;higher meaning of suffering&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

#россия #рпц

