&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&quot;With wings to the temple&quot;: how the Russian Orthodox Church talks about the &quot;apparitions&quot; of the dead invaders&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On the Orthodox portal prichod.ru, priests &lt;a href=&quot;https://prichod.ru/period-svo/47849/&quot;&gt;share stories&lt;/a&gt; about &quot;miraculous encounters&quot; with the deceased participants of the war. One military cleric recalls how a parishioner was visited in a dream by her son - with breath, a heartbeat and the words: &quot;Do not cry. The Lord welcomes us all at the gates of paradise.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In another story, a father sees his son with wings in a dream - he is hitchhiking on the side of the road and asks to be taken to the temple, where &quot;others like him, with wings&quot; are already waiting. And a soldier who escaped from the encirclement tells that before that, his deceased comrades in a dream offered to go with them &quot;to heaven&quot;, but he refused. Then he was told to go &quot;along the fireflies&quot; - and it was by them that he found his way out of the minefield.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These testimonies are described as confirmation of the spiritual reality of the war and the special participation of God in what is happening.&lt;/p&gt;

