&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;A sign marking the &quot;Site of the Victims of Political Repression in the Kuropaty Forest, 1930-1940&quot; near Minsk has disappeared.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This information appeared in the blog of pro-Russian activist Olga Bondareva, who among other things positions herself as a defender of &quot;traditional values&quot; and Orthodoxy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It should be recalled that until 2020, regular memorial services were held in Kuropaty. With the blessing of Metropolitan Pavel (Panamarov), believers led by a Belarusian Orthodox Church priest gathered here at least twice a year - on Radunitsa and Demetrius Saturday - to pray for the repressed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In 2019, the tract even ended up in the program of the BRSM action &quot;Return of Shrines. Sources of Belarus&quot;, during which Archpriest Fyodor Polny (aka &quot;the spiritual father of Lukashenko&quot;) said:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Whoever was killed and buried in this place, however many people were destroyed here - this is a tragic event! A scar on the face of humanity. The scar transforms the face of God&#x27;s creation into a bestial grimace, into a demonic image. Not specifically the image of Stalin or Yezhov, but a terrible human one. And the executioners, and the victims, and I, and you, and all of us, representatives of this humanity, embody God&#x27;s plan for man. And murder is always a step against God.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At the same time, during the Kuropaty procession of the same 2019, Polny actually approved the demolition, noting: &quot;The alleys of crosses - rather an excess of &#x27;holiness&#x27;.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After 2020, the topic of Kuropaty is completely absent from the media of the Belarusian Orthodox Church.&lt;/p&gt;

