&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;How Ukrainian churches have interpreted the war. Analysis from the Ukrainian theological journal &quot;Patriarkhat&quot;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first issue of &quot;Patriarkhat&quot; (published by the Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church) for 2025 contains an &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.patriyarkhat.org.ua/statti-zhurnalu/ukrainske-khrystyianstvo-v-ohni-publichni-zvernennia-predstoiateliv-tserkov-v-ukraini-u-pershi-misiatsi-shyrokomasshtabnoho-rosiyskoho-vtorhnennia/&quot;&gt;article&lt;/a&gt; on the public appeals of the heads of Ukrainian churches in the first weeks of the large-scale Russian invasion. The focus is on the texts of the leaders of the Orthodox Church of Ukraine, the Ukrainian Orthodox Church, the Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church, and the Roman Catholic Church in Ukraine, in which the images of Cain and Abel, Goliath, Judas, the Last Judgment, the Cross, and Golgotha are heard.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Metropolitan &lt;b&gt;Epifaniy&lt;/b&gt; (Orthodox Church of Ukraine) speaks of the right to self-defense and directly calls Russia the aggressor. The head of the Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church, &lt;b&gt;Sviatoslav Shevchuk&lt;/b&gt;, interprets the events as a spiritual struggle between good and evil, emphasizing the importance of prayer, love, and Christian discernment. The bishops of the Roman Catholic Church in Ukraine compared the war to Golgotha and called for sacrificing their sufferings for the conversion of the murderers: &quot;this is the highest form of love to which Christ calls us&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Ukrainian Orthodox Church is in solidarity with the other churches, but the tone is more restrained: there are more calls for peace, condemnation of violence, and an emphasis on the fraternal ties between the peoples.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In addition to this text, the first issue of &quot;Patriarkhat&quot; also publishes other articles devoted to how Ukrainian Christianity is responding to the challenges of wartime - on the front line, in children&#x27;s camps, in chaplaincy service, and in theological discussions.&lt;/p&gt;

