&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The Communist Party of Russia (CPRF) proposed to declare the &quot;Spas&quot; TV channel a foreign agent.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Former Novosibirsk mayor and current first secretary of the Novosibirsk regional committee of the CPRF, Anatoly Lokot, proposed to recognize the &quot;Spas&quot; TV channel as a foreign agent due to the documentary film &quot;The Mummy&quot; about Vladimir Lenin. According to him, the creation of the film was not financed from the budget. In this regard, he proposed to find out whose money was used to create the film.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;The political provocation with the screening of the &#x27;Mummy&#x27; abomination showed that we need to sort things out in our own house first. In Russia, we need to restore order with historical memory. &#x27;The Mummy&#x27; is not a blow to the party, &#x27;The Mummy&#x27; is a blow in the back of Russia, a blow to the future of Russia.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The film was made by the Orthodox TV channel &quot;Spas&quot;, owned by the Russian Orthodox Church. The annotation to it states that the film &quot;seeks an answer to the question: why was it necessary to deify the one who himself was a God-fighter, and what should we do with this legacy and the mausoleum further?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

